Adaptive query execution.

Before Spark three point zero, Catalyst made all decisions upfront using estimated statistics. Adaptive query execution re-optimizes the plan at runtime, after each shuffle, using real partition statistics.

There are three things adaptive query execution actually does.

First, dynamic coalescing. After a shuffle produces, say, two hundred partitions but most are tiny, it merges them into a smaller number of right-sized partitions. Fewer task-startup overheads.

Second, dynamic join strategy switch. A sort-merge join can be promoted to a broadcast join at runtime if one side turns out small enough.

Third, skew join handling. It splits oversized partitions so one slow task does not block the entire stage. We come back to skew in detail in the performance notebook.

Adaptive query execution is enabled by default since Spark three point two. The notebook runs the same group-by aggregation with it on and off, then prints the output partition count for each. With adaptive on, the partition count is small — coalesced from the default two hundred. With it off, the count sits at two hundred.
